In a **Terraform interview**, they may ask you to organize code into files like:

* `provider.tf`
* `data.tf`
* `variables.tf`
* `locals.tf`
* `ec2.tf`

Below is a **clean interview-standard example** to create an **EC2 instance**.

---

# 1️⃣ variables.tf

Define input variables.

```hcl
variable "aws_region" {
  type        = string
  description = "AWS Region"
  default     = "us-east-1"
}

variable "instance_type" {
  type        = string
  description = "EC2 Instance type"
  default     = "t2.micro"
}

variable "environment" {
  type        = string
  description = "Environment name"
  default     = "dev"
}
```

---

# 2️⃣ data.tf

Fetch existing AWS resources.

```hcl
data "aws_ami" "amazon_linux" {
  most_recent = true

  owners = ["amazon"]

  filter {
    name   = "name"
    values = ["amzn2-ami-hvm-*-x86_64-gp2"]
  }
}
```

This will fetch the **latest Amazon Linux AMI automatically**.

---

# 3️⃣ locals.tf

Local values used inside Terraform.

```hcl
locals {

  instance_name = "terraform-ec2-${var.environment}"

  common_tags = {
    Environment = var.environment
    Terraform   = "true"
  }

}
```

Purpose:

* Reduce repeated code
* Improve readability

---

# 4️⃣ ec2.tf

Create the EC2 instance.

```hcl
resource "aws_instance" "example" {

  ami           = data.aws_ami.amazon_linux.id
  instance_type = var.instance_type

  tags = merge(
    local.common_tags,
    {
      Name = local.instance_name
    }
  )

}
```

Explanation:

| Field         | Meaning                      |
| ------------- | ---------------------------- |
| ami           | AMI fetched from data source |
| instance_type | From variable                |
| tags          | Combine local tags           |

---

# 5️⃣ provider.tf

Configure AWS provider.

```hcl
provider "aws" {

  region = var.aws_region

}
```

---

# 📁 Final Folder Structure (Interview Best Practice)

```
terraform-project
│
├── provider.tf
├── variables.tf
├── data.tf
├── locals.tf
└── ec2.tf
```

---

# 💡 Interview Tip (Very Important)

If interviewer asks:

**Why separate files?**

Answer:

> Terraform loads all `.tf` files automatically. We split files for **better readability, modularity, and team collaboration**.

Example:

* `variables.tf` → inputs
* `data.tf` → existing resources
* `locals.tf` → reusable values
* `ec2.tf` → infrastructure resources

